Those are success stories. The vast majority of ideas die on the vine. You need either a turboaustistic amount of willpower and focus, like the DimSums and Slamanons of the world. Most people don't have that. Still, large VN and video game ideas may require cooperation like we discussed. In that case you need both turboautistic willpower and the ability to let others modify parts of your creation in a way that you didn't vision. I believe it is rare to find someone with both qualities. Usually the autists have difficulty letting other people participate because they fear it will ruin the project. Yet they are the only types who are capable of completing the development cycle to begin with. Catch-22.

Better than for a leadership position to string everyone along pretending to be active. Though once you've got a group talking, even if a founder leaves, everyone else can keep talking. That'd only be fatal if he's the only one with code skill and everyone else at the table is dime a dozen idea men who can't even Renpy.

>>69725860
>the result is so incredible when people manage to successfully team up on projects
It's a matter of personal investment.
When the VN was proposed, I thought about it, but I saw a lot of people talking about being interested but nobody talked about having any writing or programming experience. Gave me that feeling like it would be a dozen people stumping for their favorite species to make the waifur cut before the roster is full and nobody showing a portfolio that proves he can draw each character in 100 poses or write dialog better than LLM slop.

I think that the accountability/leadership issue at the start is taking responsibility of defining roles and then inviting to fill them. Like, if I were to do this project, I'd get a proof of concept with Renpy and stick figures and a small plot arc done, and then post that as a sample asking who wants to draw for something like that. And then who wants to write for something like that. You'll get people who are inspired by what they see, not just "VN sounds cool, I want to get involved because I'm curious" kinds of response. The "everyone hop into an empty conference room" strategy is both overwhelming and directionless.

>because they fear it will ruin the project
Gotta write a project bible of hard and soft limitations first so proposals can be sanity checked and perhaps negotiated.
